00:01:49.510 --> 00:01:55.200
[ Background Conversation ]

00:01:55.200 --> 00:01:57.260
&gt;&gt; Encouraged by the
success of that novel,

00:01:57.260 --> 00:01:59.600
she published a second one
called March, based on the life

00:01:59.600 --> 00:02:02.580
of Bronson Alcott and the father
figure of the Little Women

00:02:02.580 --> 00:02:06.510
and it went on to win the
Pulitzer Prize for fiction.

00:02:06.510 --> 00:02:09.380
[ Applause ]

00:02:09.380 --> 00:02:11.110
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Since then she
has published two more celebrated

00:02:11.110 --> 00:02:14.760
novels, People of the
Book and Caleb's Crossing.

00:02:17.040 --> 00:02:19.340
Now all of her novels
have been dramatic works

00:02:19.340 --> 00:02:22.610
of historical reclamation and
imagination, but her upcoming,

00:02:22.610 --> 00:02:27.480
her new book, The Secret Chord,
is her most ambitious work yet.

00:02:27.480 --> 00:02:32.980
The Secret Chord is about David,
King David, ruler of Judah,

00:02:32.980 --> 00:02:35.870
ancestor of Jesus,
Michelangelo's subject

00:02:35.870 --> 00:02:39.480
for the first Abercrombie
and Fitch model.

00:02:39.480 --> 00:02:42.180
The story is incredible, I
mean I thought I knew this

00:02:42.180 --> 00:02:46.840 position:56%
from my Sunday school days, but wow,
it's got war, intrigue, betrayal,

00:02:46.840 --> 00:02:49.010
sex, it's one spectacular scandal

00:02:49.010 --> 00:02:52.320
after another even by
Washington standards.

00:02:53.370 --> 00:02:55.130
You are in for a treat
for Geraldine Brooks,

00:02:55.130 --> 00:02:57.670
tells us about her
inspiration, her research,

00:02:57.670 --> 00:03:00.580
and her work to bring this
ancient hero to new life.

00:03:00.580 --> 00:03:03.510
Please join me in welcoming her.

00:03:03.510 --> 00:03:11.540
[ Applause ]

00:03:11.540 --> 00:03:14.350
&gt;&gt; Geraldine Brooks: Thank you,
Ron, you really are my hero.

00:03:14.350 --> 00:03:18.930
He is just the best,
and may I just recommend

00:03:18.930 --> 00:03:25.780
to your attention Ron has another
hat as well being a book reviewer

00:03:25.780 --> 00:03:29.990
for the Washington Post, he is
also the totally hip book reviewer

00:03:29.990 --> 00:03:33.920
on YouTube, and those of you
that haven't had the pleasure

00:03:33.920 --> 00:03:38.880
of seeing his work there, Ron.

00:03:38.880 --> 00:03:44.660
So I'm the kind of person who
tends to be as Zen as possible

00:03:44.660 --> 00:03:48.500
about doing events like this.

00:03:48.500 --> 00:03:49.800
Thank you all for coming.

00:03:49.800 --> 00:03:52.260
It's hard to be Zen with
this many people in the room.

00:03:52.260 --> 00:03:57.680
And particularly when I
read the author instructions

00:03:57.680 --> 00:04:02.360
that the National Book Festival
thoughtfully sends to us,

00:04:02.360 --> 00:04:05.140
and it said to be personal.

00:04:05.140 --> 00:04:06.440
So that's okay.

00:04:06.440 --> 00:04:10.620
So I loaded up a power point
with some slides of my kids,

00:04:10.620 --> 00:04:12.440
which I will show you soon.

00:04:12.440 --> 00:04:17.940
And then they said
don't use any notes.

00:04:17.940 --> 00:04:21.720
And I'm, what do we think we are?

00:04:21.720 --> 00:04:26.420
We're people who spend 90%
of our lives alone in a room

00:04:26.420 --> 00:04:30.550
because we're really quite shy.

00:04:30.550 --> 00:04:32.260
Don't use any notes?

00:04:32.260 --> 00:04:38.840
As you see, I am flouting
that instruction.

00:04:38.840 --> 00:04:43.090
I will try to not to refer to
them too much, but like Linus,

00:04:43.090 --> 00:04:45.150
I need my security blanket.

00:04:45.150 --> 00:04:48.470
I hope for your understanding.

00:04:48.470 --> 00:04:52.380
But to try and fulfill the
requirement of being personable,

00:04:52.380 --> 00:04:57.030
I thought I would share
with you some information

00:04:57.030 --> 00:04:58.790
about the thing I collect.

00:04:58.790 --> 00:05:03.510
I think most people, or many
people, have collections.

00:05:03.510 --> 00:05:08.270
Some people have coins or
stamps or bobble headed dolls,

00:05:08.270 --> 00:05:13.510
I collect examples
of unhelpful signage.

00:05:13.510 --> 00:05:18.040
[ Laughter ]

00:05:18.040 --> 00:05:19.340
&gt;&gt; Geraldine Brooks: Watch

00:05:19.340 --> 00:05:23.500
for falling rocks is a
perennial favorite of mine.

00:05:23.500 --> 00:05:29.700
It's the rare ones I treasure, like
bird watcher heading to Antarctica

00:05:29.700 --> 00:05:33.020
or the Galapagos and such,
there's a blue footed booby

00:05:33.020 --> 00:05:35.460
that can be seen no where else.

00:05:35.460 --> 00:05:38.510
I like those signs that
you have to travel to get.

00:05:38.510 --> 00:05:41.970
And a lot of them are in my
home country of Australia.

00:05:41.970 --> 00:05:47.260
In far north Queensland where
the roads are often more notional

00:05:47.260 --> 00:05:54.690
than actual, there's the sign
that says drive according

00:05:54.690 --> 00:05:57.280
to prevailing conditions.

00:05:58.300 --> 00:06:05.180
Even better at a place aptly named
Big Hole in the northern territory,

00:06:05.180 --> 00:06:09.060
accidents can lead
to injury and death.

00:06:10.320 --> 00:06:15.060
Um, there was a sign I saw on
over an expressway in Florida

00:06:15.060 --> 00:06:18.650
that first looked like
helpful information,

00:06:18.650 --> 00:06:22.050
texting while driving kills.

00:06:22.050 --> 00:06:24.860
Fair enough I thought, and
then I noticed at the bottom

00:06:24.860 --> 00:06:32.870
of the sign it said, for
safety tips, text #safety.

00:06:32.870 --> 00:06:39.130
But perhaps the prize in
my collection is the sign

00:06:39.130 --> 00:06:42.230
on the car ferry that goes
back and forth to my home

00:06:42.230 --> 00:06:48.780
on Martha's Vineyard,
for your safety,

00:06:48.780 --> 00:06:53.470
please exit the freight deck
while the vessel is underway.

00:06:53.470 --> 00:06:56.900
I love that sign.

00:06:56.900 --> 00:07:01.530
Every time I see it, it makes me
laugh because I get this vision

00:07:01.530 --> 00:07:06.740
of all the vacation SUVs with
their bungee Chorded extrusions

00:07:06.740 --> 00:07:10.390
of bicycles and kayaks and
spare blankets and pillows

00:07:10.390 --> 00:07:12.810
and all the holiday paraphernalia,

00:07:12.810 --> 00:07:19.330
obediently driving off the
freight deck into Vineyard Sound.

00:07:19.330 --> 00:07:24.380
And I thought, well that's one
way to thin out the August crowds.

00:07:24.380 --> 00:07:27.700
So why do I like these
signs so much?

00:07:27.700 --> 00:07:34.030
It's because they remind me how
magnificently complicated our

00:07:34.030 --> 00:07:39.980
language is and how difficult
it is to convey precise meaning,

00:07:39.980 --> 00:07:43.120
no matter how well
intentioned you are.

00:07:43.120 --> 00:07:46.600
Somebody at the Martha's Vineyard
Steamship Authority probably put a

00:07:46.600 --> 00:07:49.860
lot of thought into that
sign and getting made

00:07:49.860 --> 00:07:54.090
up in nice high-vis lettering, and
they just wanted to advise people

00:07:54.090 --> 00:07:57.620
to get out of their cars for
the duration of the trip.

00:07:57.620 --> 00:07:59.900
And yet they totally blew it.

00:07:59.900 --> 00:08:06.590 position:56%
So I keep little sticky notes of
these signs on the desk in my study,

00:08:06.590 --> 00:08:09.540
and it's to remind me
to be extra careful

00:08:09.540 --> 00:08:13.040
with this fragile treasure,
our language.

00:08:13.040 --> 00:08:17.520
But like the Steamship Authority
wiz, I often blow it, too.

00:08:17.520 --> 00:08:21.770
The difference between the
right word and the wrong word

00:08:21.770 --> 00:08:25.480
as Mark Twain told
us, is the difference

00:08:25.480 --> 00:08:28.990
between lightning and
the lightning bug.

00:08:28.990 --> 00:08:34.350 position:56%
And when you're writing historical
fiction the stakes here can be quite

00:08:34.350 --> 00:08:37.490
high because if you
put the wrong word

00:08:37.490 --> 00:08:41.420
in a character's mouth you can
pull your reader out of the time

00:08:41.420 --> 00:08:46.950 position:56%
and place that you're trying to keep
them in and that is unfortunate.

00:08:46.950 --> 00:08:51.510
So I've done that, I have to admit.

00:08:51.510 --> 00:09:01.350
In Year of Wonders, my first novel,
I have my 1665 young heroine,

00:09:01.350 --> 00:09:06.300
waxing eloquently about the
mauve tide of the Heather moving

00:09:06.300 --> 00:09:10.740
across the mountainside of
her peak district, Home Place.

00:09:10.740 --> 00:09:18.760
Problem, the first use of the word
mauve as a color wasn't until 1796.

00:09:18.760 --> 00:09:25.190
I know that because somebody
actually wrote a book titled Mauve,

00:09:25.190 --> 00:09:29.210
How One Man Invented a Color
that Changed the World.

00:09:29.210 --> 00:09:36.240
Whoops. So it was not long
after that novel came out,

00:09:36.240 --> 00:09:38.620
and I think I was speaking
about it in England,

00:09:38.620 --> 00:09:43.660
and I met a wonderful English
novelist called Jim Crace,

00:09:43.660 --> 00:09:47.860
who had written a book
set in biblical Israel,

00:09:47.860 --> 00:09:50.480
called Quarantines,
it's a wonderful novel.

00:09:50.480 --> 00:09:54.030
And he was telling me about how
he researched that novel and a lot

00:09:54.030 --> 00:09:59.260
of his research had to do with
camping in the Judean Desert

00:09:59.260 --> 00:10:03.540
to get the sense of the place
and he said, on the first morning

00:10:03.540 --> 00:10:09.050
of this camping trip, his
Bedouin guide woke him with a cup

00:10:09.050 --> 00:10:13.190
of lovely cardamom
scented Arabic coffee

00:10:13.190 --> 00:10:16.460 position:56%
and said Mr. Jim, how did you sleep?

00:10:16.460 --> 00:10:20.060
And he said Ahmed I
slept like a log.

00:10:20.060 --> 00:10:21.810
&gt;&gt; And then he said
he raised his eyes

00:10:21.810 --> 00:10:24.010
to the bare rock ribbed hillsides

00:10:24.010 --> 00:10:28.990
of the Judean Desert,
not a log to be seen.

00:10:28.990 --> 00:10:36.280
So he turned to his guide and he
said Ahmed, how did you sleep?

00:10:36.280 --> 00:10:41.630
And Ahmed said, Mr. Jim, I
slept like a dead donkey.

00:10:41.630 --> 00:10:47.520
So ever since Jim Crace
shared that story with me,

00:10:47.520 --> 00:10:52.300
I spent a lot of time going over my
manuscripts and trying to find logs

00:10:52.300 --> 00:10:54.380
and turn them into dead donkeys.

00:10:54.380 --> 00:10:56.990
So I hope when you read
my books you'll find a lot

00:10:56.990 --> 00:11:00.060
of dead donkeys in them.

00:11:00.060 --> 00:11:02.110
It's not always easy.

00:11:02.110 --> 00:11:05.070
In The Secret Chord for example,

00:11:05.070 --> 00:11:08.440
which is set in second
iron age Israel,

00:11:08.440 --> 00:11:11.360
I kept running into a lot of logs.

00:11:11.360 --> 00:11:14.820
I had to take out the word assassin

00:11:14.820 --> 00:11:19.230
because the original assassins
were violent Persian sect

00:11:19.230 --> 00:11:22.780
of the 11th century and that's not
likely my Hebrew tribesman would

00:11:22.780 --> 00:11:24.830
have been talking about them.

00:11:24.830 --> 00:11:29.060
I substituted the word
thug, only to realize

00:11:29.060 --> 00:11:34.020
that that was actually a
violent group of Indian outlaws

00:11:34.020 --> 00:11:38.260
from the 15th century and my
Hebrews would not have been talking

00:11:38.260 --> 00:11:39.560
about them either.

00:11:39.560 --> 00:11:44.440
So I didn't find a really
good dead donkey in that case,

00:11:44.440 --> 00:11:47.050
but sometimes you can
find them and I think

00:11:47.050 --> 00:11:50.000
that the effect is
well worth the effort.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:53.900
So in Caleb's Crossing, my
young narrator needs to talk

00:11:53.900 --> 00:12:01.110
about a foetus and I'm pretty sure
that in Massachusetts in 1660,

00:12:01.110 --> 00:12:03.850
she's not using the word foetus.

00:12:03.850 --> 00:12:06.170
And lucky for me there's
a wonderful resource,

00:12:06.170 --> 00:12:10.990
the Oxford Historical Thesaurus
of the English Language that digs

00:12:10.990 --> 00:12:17.090 position:56%
down on every word in use from today
all the way to early Icelandic,

00:12:17.090 --> 00:12:23.890 position:56%
and so if you look up foetus you can
go down to mid 17th century and find

00:12:23.890 --> 00:12:26.730
that the word she probably
would have used is shapeling.

00:12:26.730 --> 00:12:32.120
If you put the word
shapeling into her mouth,

00:12:32.120 --> 00:12:34.650
I think you can time travel.

00:12:34.650 --> 00:12:37.900
So does it really matter?

00:12:37.900 --> 00:12:43.420
Is it important or is
it just nit picking?

00:12:43.420 --> 00:12:48.780
An expression, I have to say, that
I've loved for it's aptness ever

00:12:48.780 --> 00:12:52.990
since my son got head
lice in the third grade.

00:12:52.990 --> 00:12:56.010
It really is very exacting work.

00:12:56.010 --> 00:13:01.170
But I think combing
through a manuscript looking

00:13:01.170 --> 00:13:06.810
for bad vocabulary is in some
ways very similar to nit picking,

00:13:06.810 --> 00:13:08.390
and I think it does matter.

00:13:08.390 --> 00:13:11.470
And I think it's respectful
to you, the reader.

00:13:11.470 --> 00:13:13.080
And I'll tell you why.

00:13:13.080 --> 00:13:17.560
Not that many years ago, I had
a wonderful year as a fellow

00:13:17.560 --> 00:13:22.850
at The Radcliffe Institute for
Advanced Studies at Harvard,

00:13:22.850 --> 00:13:26.350
and this is just a
terrific boondoggle,

00:13:26.350 --> 00:13:32.090 position:56%
they pay you to do your own work
and to have lunch with other fellows

00:13:32.090 --> 00:13:36.570
who come from a diversity of fields
across the sciences and the arts

00:13:36.570 --> 00:13:40.220
and academics, and you
give each other ideas

00:13:40.220 --> 00:13:43.480
and it's just a great experience,
and your only obligation is

00:13:43.480 --> 00:13:45.880
to give one talk on what
you're working on and go

00:13:45.880 --> 00:13:48.740 position:56%
to the talks of your fellow fellows.

00:13:48.740 --> 00:13:54.980
So one of my fellow fellows was
a mathematician from Bordeaux,

00:13:54.980 --> 00:14:01.570
and her talk was entitled
Singularities

00:14:01.570 --> 00:14:03.530
in Algebraic Plane Curves.

00:14:03.530 --> 00:14:12.750
And I have to tell you, I
slumped into that lecture room.

00:14:12.750 --> 00:14:19.230 position:56%
I took a doodle pad and I thought if
I positioned myself behind a pillow,

00:14:19.230 --> 00:14:23.440
a short nap might not
be out of the question.

00:14:23.440 --> 00:14:27.020
Math was my not my strong suit.

00:14:27.020 --> 00:14:31.050
But on that pad that
I carried that day,

00:14:31.050 --> 00:14:33.190
I found that my doodles
quickly turned

00:14:33.190 --> 00:14:35.940 position:56%
to notations of what she was saying.

00:14:35.940 --> 00:14:40.400
And here's a couple of things
that I wrote down that she said.

00:14:40.400 --> 00:14:47.770
A formal power series about the
original is an infinite sum.

00:14:47.770 --> 00:14:52.890
Homomorphism is an
isomorphism if and only

00:14:52.890 --> 00:14:57.290
if the matrix is invertible.

00:14:57.290 --> 00:15:01.970
This is like poetry I thought,
and I leaned in to hear more.

00:15:01.970 --> 00:15:06.350
She was eloquent and she was
passionate and what she did was,

00:15:06.350 --> 00:15:09.720
as soon as I gave up the idea I
couldn't understand a word she was

00:15:09.720 --> 00:15:11.630 position:56%
saying, she cracked open the airlock

00:15:11.630 --> 00:15:14.740
and showed me a glimpse
of her world.

00:15:14.740 --> 00:15:17.740
And I now know that
it's a beautiful world.

00:15:17.740 --> 00:15:22.230
What she was doing was trying to
find that place in every curve

00:15:22.230 --> 00:15:28.400
that is singular and she was trying
to express more perfectly the truth

00:15:28.400 --> 00:15:31.830
about the world, and I
realized that that is what I

00:15:31.830 --> 00:15:36.810
as a novelist also must do, is
to delve in and find the singular

00:15:36.810 --> 00:15:41.420
and get as close as possible to
the truth of the world as I can.

00:15:41.420 --> 00:15:46.150
And so it's a beautiful world
but I can't live in her world

00:15:46.150 --> 00:15:50.790 position:56%
because if she's got lungs I've got
gills, I work completely differently

00:15:50.790 --> 00:15:53.420
and my work is all about words.

00:15:53.420 --> 00:15:58.290
I didn't start out as a novelist,
I started out as a journalist

00:15:58.290 --> 00:16:03.320
and I loved every step I
took in that occupation.

00:16:03.320 --> 00:16:08.820 position:56%
But when my son was born 20 years
ago I realized I no longer wanted be

00:16:08.820 --> 00:16:13.030
a foreign correspondent going off
on long, open ended assignments,

00:16:13.030 --> 00:16:16.080
and so I had to see if I
could do something else.

00:16:16.080 --> 00:16:20.400
And I wrote Year of
Wonders and lucky for me,

00:16:20.400 --> 00:16:22.590
many of you wanted to read it.

00:16:22.590 --> 00:16:24.960
So I got to keep doing that.

00:16:24.960 --> 00:16:29.560
But I have that son to
thank for the inspiration

00:16:29.560 --> 00:16:33.070
for my most recent
novel, The Secret Chord

00:16:33.070 --> 00:16:38.570
because when he was just nine
years old he took the very unusual,

00:16:38.570 --> 00:16:41.120
I think, decision for
a boy of that age

00:16:41.120 --> 00:16:43.670
that the one musical
instrument he was interested

00:16:43.670 --> 00:16:47.190
in learning was the classical harp.

00:16:47.190 --> 00:16:51.870
I had been braced for drums
so I didn't resist the choice.

00:16:51.870 --> 00:16:56.190
But, it was watching him dwarfed

00:16:56.190 --> 00:17:01.330
by his teacher's beautiful concert
instrument, that set me back

00:17:01.330 --> 00:17:04.940
to thinking about David,
that avid boy harpist,

00:17:04.940 --> 00:17:08.110
that musician whose
music was so powerful

00:17:08.110 --> 00:17:10.160
that it could soothe
the mentally ill

00:17:10.160 --> 00:17:13.640
and even please God in
Heaven so we're told.

00:17:13.640 --> 00:17:18.100 position:56%
And I had been a Fine Arts major in
college and I'd been very interested

00:17:18.100 --> 00:17:21.140
in the various depictions of David

00:17:21.140 --> 00:17:24.590
in Italian Renaissance
and baroque art.

00:17:24.590 --> 00:17:33.260
This shepherd, this warrior, this
musician, this complicated man,

00:17:33.260 --> 00:17:39.610 position:56%
this man that we know, perhaps
before we know any other human being

00:17:39.610 --> 00:17:43.990
in full from early
childhood to extreme old age,

00:17:43.990 --> 00:17:48.040
he's really the first
political biography we have.

00:17:48.040 --> 00:17:51.980
A man who is very recognizably
human without a lot

00:17:51.980 --> 00:17:57.920
of supernatural interventions in
his life, and when I went back

00:17:57.920 --> 00:17:59.290
and read the Books Samuel,

00:17:59.290 --> 00:18:02.200
I realized that absolutely
everything happens to him

00:18:02.200 --> 00:18:06.630 position:56%
in his long life, every good
experience and every bad experience,

00:18:06.630 --> 00:18:10.820
every powerful emotion that the
human heart could encompass,

00:18:10.820 --> 00:18:13.310
and I wanted to tell the story.

00:18:13.310 --> 00:18:17.520
But I like to tell my stories
with a first person narrator,

00:18:17.520 --> 00:18:20.150
and I wasn't sure who that
should be in this case.

00:18:20.150 --> 00:18:22.160
I knew it couldn't be David himself

00:18:22.160 --> 00:18:27.620
because he wouldn't have
enough objectivity to look

00:18:27.620 --> 00:18:30.940
at his own character and he
certainly wouldn't be able

00:18:30.940 --> 00:18:37.740
to effectively tell the story
of the women in his life

00:18:37.740 --> 00:18:41.220 position:56%
because if he had understood them he
wouldn't have treated them the way

00:18:41.220 --> 00:18:42.920
he did.

00:18:42.920 --> 00:18:47.700
And then I came across
two references in the Book

00:18:47.700 --> 00:18:53.380
of Chronicles, intriguing
references to the Book of Nathan,

00:18:53.380 --> 00:18:59.330
and those two quotes that tell
us that the life of David,

00:18:59.330 --> 00:19:01.910
all his acts from first to last,

00:19:01.910 --> 00:19:07.690
have been set down by the
prophet Nathan, really inspired me

00:19:07.690 --> 00:19:12.320
because those of you that paid
attention in religious school,

00:19:12.320 --> 00:19:16.890
will remember that Nathan is
the one man who's brave enough

00:19:16.890 --> 00:19:20.750
to confront the king
about his moral failings.

00:19:20.750 --> 00:19:22.760
He's the one who tells David

00:19:22.760 --> 00:19:27.790
that he's completely
betrayed his own best self,

00:19:27.790 --> 00:19:31.490
tells him what the
consequences of this will be.

00:19:31.490 --> 00:19:38.670 position:56%
And when you read his ferocious
castigation of the king, you wonder,

00:19:38.670 --> 00:19:40.660
what was the career
path for that guy?

00:19:40.660 --> 00:19:45.970
Because usually if you say
that kind of a thing to a king,

00:19:45.970 --> 00:19:48.640
that's the last thing
you get to say.

00:19:48.640 --> 00:19:51.250
But what's wonderful
about this story is

00:19:51.250 --> 00:19:58.290
that David accepts
responsibility, accepts the truth

00:19:58.290 --> 00:20:02.090
of what Nathan has said,
and how unusual is that?

00:20:02.090 --> 00:20:05.790
&gt;&gt; When have you ever
heard a politician say yep!

00:20:05.790 --> 00:20:08.830
You got me, I did it!

00:20:08.830 --> 00:20:13.860
No, it's always, I did not
have sex with that woman.

00:20:13.860 --> 00:20:15.700
He said, yeah I did and
that was really wrong

00:20:15.700 --> 00:20:17.000
and I shouldn't have
killed her husband,

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:19.760
and then he brings Nathan
closer so that at the end

00:20:19.760 --> 00:20:23.960
of his life it's not Nathan that
he turns to, to resolve the issues

00:20:23.960 --> 00:20:27.320
of succession and to make sure
that the king who succeeds him

00:20:27.320 --> 00:20:30.570
on this throne is the one
son who should do that,

00:20:30.570 --> 00:20:34.560
because he's Solomon who's
come down to us as the bi-word

00:20:34.560 --> 00:20:36.860
for wisdom and good governance.

00:20:36.860 --> 00:20:40.540
So, I knew my narrator
was going to be Nathan,

00:20:40.540 --> 00:20:42.690
but I wasn't sure what his
voice would sound like.

00:20:42.690 --> 00:20:46.080
I imagined at first that he
would have a very tough voice,

00:20:46.080 --> 00:20:52.430
that this would be a power
broker, a mafia consigliere,

00:20:52.430 --> 00:20:58.520
or maybe a Thomas Cromwell,
Henry the 8th's dark imminence.

00:20:58.520 --> 00:21:03.170
And then I thought maybe
something really creepy.

00:21:04.710 --> 00:21:10.150
But Nathan didn't want
to be any of those guys,

00:21:10.150 --> 00:21:14.480
he refused to speak
in that voice to me.

00:21:14.480 --> 00:21:17.740
He had something completely
different in mind.

00:21:17.740 --> 00:21:20.710
He wanted to sound like these guys.

00:21:21.730 --> 00:21:26.120
He wanted to be unworldly,
he wanted to be idealistic,

00:21:26.120 --> 00:21:30.740
he wanted to be the light in
the story, and of course he does

00:21:30.740 --> 00:21:32.910
because he's a Hebrew prophet.

00:21:32.910 --> 00:21:37.290
And that's what these guys are
like, that is how they roll.

00:21:37.290 --> 00:21:40.460
They're the ones who bring us to
our best self, so I had to give

00:21:40.460 --> 00:21:42.200
in and let him be that guy.

00:21:42.200 --> 00:21:45.040
But then how was I going
to research this book?

00:21:45.040 --> 00:21:49.400
Usually I dive into archives and
read all the journals and letters

00:21:49.400 --> 00:21:53.110
and court reChords where
you can hear people

00:21:53.110 --> 00:21:55.880
in verbatim testimony
speaking in their own voice,

00:21:55.880 --> 00:21:58.830
so I can get the sound of
the language in my head.

00:21:58.830 --> 00:22:01.640
That wasn't going to be
possible in this case,

00:22:01.640 --> 00:22:06.920
so I realized that I would have
to do a more experiential kind

00:22:06.920 --> 00:22:10.480
of research, and I took a leaf out
of Jim Crace's book and headed off

00:22:10.480 --> 00:22:13.320
to Israel with my youngest son.

00:22:13.320 --> 00:22:17.850
I told you there would be
family photos, and here's one.

00:22:17.850 --> 00:22:22.030
I love exploiting my children
as research assistants.

00:22:22.030 --> 00:22:25.350
They see things very freshly
and they ask questions

00:22:25.350 --> 00:22:30.970
that we wouldn't think to ask,
so I thought, what can we do

00:22:30.970 --> 00:22:33.070
that is similar to
the kinds of things

00:22:33.070 --> 00:22:37.160
that David might have
done 3,000 years ago?

00:22:37.160 --> 00:22:40.330
Not the adultery and
the murder so much.

00:22:40.330 --> 00:22:44.980
Herding sheep was the first one
because of course so many leaders

00:22:44.980 --> 00:22:48.630
in the bible start off as
shepherds and I was wondering,

00:22:48.630 --> 00:22:52.350
what is it about the business
about herding sheep that turns

00:22:52.350 --> 00:22:56.890
out to be a great entry level
position for future CEOs of Israel?

00:22:56.890 --> 00:23:02.190
And I found in that long
afternoon that my son

00:23:02.190 --> 00:23:07.480
and I were herding those sheep
on the hillside in Israel,

00:23:07.480 --> 00:23:11.900
that you have to understand
those that you're trying to lead.

00:23:11.900 --> 00:23:15.050
We were trying to separate the
sheep from the goats which turns

00:23:15.050 --> 00:23:19.060
out to be just as hard in real
life as the metaphor suggests.

00:23:19.060 --> 00:23:21.290
And you can't do it
until you understand

00:23:21.290 --> 00:23:24.230
that goats react differently
to pressure to sheep.

00:23:24.230 --> 00:23:27.880
So once we had that insight, I
realized that I was going to use

00:23:27.880 --> 00:23:34.520
that and let David have that
kind of insight about leadership.

00:23:34.520 --> 00:23:38.510
So we then did other things,
we stayed in the desert

00:23:38.510 --> 00:23:42.820 position:56%
in goat head tents, eating the kinds
of foods mentioned in the bible,

00:23:42.820 --> 00:23:47.920 position:56%
and we drew water from ancient
systems to feel the effort involved,

00:23:47.920 --> 00:23:53.790
and we rode camels only
to find when we got home

00:23:53.790 --> 00:23:57.380 position:56%
that we'd got a sore backside for
nothing because there were no camels

00:23:57.380 --> 00:24:02.020
in Second Iron Age Israel, and
