00:32:14.130 --> 00:32:15.430
I've read.

00:32:15.430 --> 00:32:16.730
She's a poet and a violinist,

00:32:16.730 --> 00:32:19.410
so she knows what she's doing
with language and music.

00:32:19.410 --> 00:32:20.980
So I loved that.

00:32:20.980 --> 00:32:27.460
And then a little memoir
called The Point of Vanishing,

00:32:27.460 --> 00:32:32.700
which is a true story of
a young man at Harvard

00:32:32.700 --> 00:32:38.270
who has a horrible accident that
destroys his sight in one eye

00:32:38.270 --> 00:32:41.140
and sends him into a tailspin,
and he goes off to live

00:32:41.140 --> 00:32:43.330
in the woods, a bit like Thoreau.

00:32:43.330 --> 00:32:46.050
And he's a worthy successor
to Thoreau.

00:32:46.050 --> 00:32:47.650
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:32:47.650 --> 00:32:48.950
&gt;&gt; Geraldine Brooks: So, yeah.

00:32:48.950 --> 00:32:50.500
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:32:50.500 --> 00:32:51.800
&gt;&gt; Thank you so much.

00:32:51.800 --> 00:32:55.050
Your books have been a thread
throughout the four different

00:32:55.050 --> 00:32:59.810
generations of my family, and
we really enjoy reading them,

00:32:59.810 --> 00:33:02.010
and each of us our favorite.

00:33:02.010 --> 00:33:03.520
&gt;&gt; Geraldine Brooks:
Oh, that's lovely.

00:33:03.520 --> 00:33:07.930 position:56%
&gt;&gt; And I was curious, I imagine
writing a book, each is so distinct,

00:33:07.930 --> 00:33:13.140
but if in the different processes
of writing your different novels,

00:33:13.140 --> 00:33:16.690
if there was one novel that
you enjoyed writing the most?

00:33:16.690 --> 00:33:20.390
And if there's one you enjoyed
the final product the most?

00:33:20.390 --> 00:33:22.500
&gt;&gt; Geraldine Brooks: You
know, it sounds like a cliché

00:33:22.500 --> 00:33:25.960
but they really are like your
children, and it's really hard

00:33:25.960 --> 00:33:31.110
to pick a favorite of them, because
they're bound up with that time

00:33:31.110 --> 00:33:34.050
in your life, and you remember
exactly where you were,

00:33:34.050 --> 00:33:36.300
what room you were in when
you were writing them,

00:33:36.300 --> 00:33:39.090
and how old your children
were, and the various struggles

00:33:39.090 --> 00:33:41.560
that you had around writing them.

00:33:41.560 --> 00:33:47.020
And you know, you always love your
first novel, I have to love March

00:33:47.020 --> 00:33:49.420
because it brought
me the Pulitzer Prize

00:33:49.420 --> 00:33:51.630 position:56%
and there's nothing wrong with that.

00:33:51.630 --> 00:33:54.240
You know, people sometimes
say doesn't it put a lot

00:33:54.240 --> 00:33:55.540
of pressure on you?

00:33:55.540 --> 00:33:56.840
And I go, hell no.

00:33:56.840 --> 00:34:01.390
And you know, so it was
so outside of anything

00:34:01.390 --> 00:34:03.660
that I even would have
imagined was possible.

00:34:03.660 --> 00:34:08.430
I was so shocked the day the phone
rang and it was an old colleague

00:34:08.430 --> 00:34:10.580
of mine actually, from the
newspaper I used to work at,

00:34:10.580 --> 00:34:13.080
The Wall Street Journal, and
he thought I already knew,

00:34:13.080 --> 00:34:15.520
and he's like this is so great.

00:34:15.520 --> 00:34:16.820
This is so wonderful.

00:34:16.820 --> 00:34:19.400
And I thought, it's three o'clock
and Ken's been out to a long lunch.

00:34:19.400 --> 00:34:21.350
What is he talking about?

00:34:21.350 --> 00:34:24.170
And he said, you don't know
you got the Pulitzer Prize?

00:34:24.170 --> 00:34:27.960
And I said don't be so ridiculous,
I haven't done any journalism.

00:34:27.960 --> 00:34:29.610
And I hung up on him.

00:34:29.610 --> 00:34:34.410
And then you know, of course,
everything explodes and I realize

00:34:34.410 --> 00:34:38.370
that as unlikely as it seemed, this
was true, and somebody's coming

00:34:38.370 --> 00:34:41.690 position:56%
to the door with flowers, and I'm
on the phone to a newspaper reporter

00:34:41.690 --> 00:34:45.100
and my son, who is eight at
the time, opened the door

00:34:45.100 --> 00:34:50.840
and said mom can't
come, she's really busy.

00:34:50.840 --> 00:34:54.510
She just got the Pulitzer Surprise!

00:34:54.510 --> 00:35:01.050
[ Laughter ]

00:35:01.050 --> 00:35:05.360
&gt;&gt; So I'm sorry, I can't
really narrow it down to one.

00:35:05.360 --> 00:35:07.560
Okay, so I'm getting the wind up.

00:35:07.560 --> 00:35:10.190
Can we just take one more question?

00:35:10.190 --> 00:35:11.490
&gt;&gt; Sure.

00:35:11.490 --> 00:35:12.790
&gt;&gt; Geraldine Brooks: Okay.

00:35:12.790 --> 00:35:14.090
&gt;&gt; I've loved your
writing, all your books,

00:35:14.090 --> 00:35:18.860 position:56%
but one I recently finished was
Caleb's Crossing and I love the part

00:35:18.860 --> 00:35:21.290 position:56%
where the scholars are all so skinny

00:35:21.290 --> 00:35:23.920
because they can't afford
anything at Harvard.

00:35:23.920 --> 00:35:27.300 position:56%
They can't afford to feed them even.

00:35:27.300 --> 00:35:28.600
&gt;&gt; Geraldine Brooks: Yes.

00:35:28.600 --> 00:35:30.090
&gt;&gt; I just wondered how they
did not have an endowment?

00:35:30.090 --> 00:35:32.540
&gt;&gt; Geraldine Brooks:
No, not at that time.

00:35:32.540 --> 00:35:36.710
&gt;&gt; I just wondered what was the
overheard conversation or the.

00:35:36.710 --> 00:35:38.480
&gt;&gt; Geraldine Brooks: That
was a notation on a map

00:35:38.480 --> 00:35:41.050
of the island of Martha's Vineyard.

00:35:41.050 --> 00:35:44.940
We had just moved there as year
round residents and I was intrigued

00:35:44.940 --> 00:35:47.570
to have Native American
neighbors for the first time,

00:35:47.570 --> 00:35:52.210 position:56%
so I went to the tribal headquarters
and got all the materials,

00:35:52.210 --> 00:35:54.310
and that's a fantastic
tribe you know,

00:35:54.310 --> 00:35:57.250
because they've never been
displaced from their land

00:35:57.250 --> 00:35:59.660
and they're fantastic
custodians of their culture.

00:35:59.660 --> 00:36:02.780
And they had this map of the
island with all the notations

00:36:02.780 --> 00:36:05.760
of the place names in
the Wampanoag language,

00:36:05.760 --> 00:36:07.880
and places of significance,
and right near

00:36:07.880 --> 00:36:10.820
where we were living it
said birthplace of Caleb,

00:36:10.820 --> 00:36:12.930
first Native American
graduate of Harvard.

00:36:12.930 --> 00:36:18.880
And my eye couldn't actually
accept that the next bit was 1665.

00:36:18.880 --> 00:36:21.660
I had to read it as
1965 because it was

00:36:21.660 --> 00:36:25.690
so beyond what I would
have considered possible.

00:36:25.690 --> 00:36:29.080
And then when I found
out it really was 1665,

00:36:29.080 --> 00:36:32.540
I was, how did that happen?

00:36:32.540 --> 00:36:33.840
And what was it like?

00:36:33.840 --> 00:36:36.160
And then I was off to the races.

00:36:36.160 --> 00:36:37.940
And that's generally how it does.

00:36:37.940 --> 00:36:39.240
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

